# Enable WSL + Install Kali (step-by-step)
# Open PowerShell (Admin) and enable required features:
# Enable WSL and Virtual Machine Platform
# To see the available distros for WSL you can run "wsl --list --online"
Ubuntu: (various versions like Ubuntu 24.04 LTS, 22.04 LTS, 20.04 LTS, etc.)
Debian GNU/Linux
Kali Linux
openSUSE Leap
SUSE Linux Enterprise Server
Oracle Linux: (various versions like 9.1, 8.7, etc.)
AlmaLinux
Arch Linux

wsl --install -d kali-linux
If wsl --install is not available (older Windows), run:
# legacy method
dism.exe /online /enable-feature /featurename:VirtualMachinePlatform /all /norestart
dism.exe /online /enable-feature /featurename:Microsoft-Windows-Subsystem-Linux /all /norestart
# then restart Windows, then:
wsl --set-default-version 2
# Install Kali from store or manually import a distro
After installation: launch Kali from Start menu or run:
wsl -d kali-linux
----------------------------------
| Windows PowerShell (Admin) |
| > wsl --install -d kali-linux |
| Installing, please wait... |
| Done. Launching kali-linux... |
----------------------------------

# Once Linux is launched it will have you create a username and password.  You're going to want to update the Linux distro in the same manner that you would any other:
sudo apt update  && sudo apt upgrade
# You now have a working Linux distro that you can use.
